Santander Bank Customers Satisfaction - Data Analytics Project

1.0 The Context and Understanding the Business

  1. The Context
    2. The Santander Bank provided an anonymized dataset with a large of numeric variables. The "TARGET" column is the variable to predict. It equals one for unsatisfied customers and 0 for satisfied customers.
  2. The Business Chalenge
    3. Provide by Data Analytics Solution the probability that a customer will position yourself as unsatisfied.
  3. My Goals
    4. Provide this Data Analytics Solution using PySpark (Python + Spark) generating a predict model with the best accuracy and showing certain proficient level with Spark and Python Technologies passing per all project steps.

2.0 Business Context

    2.1 Satisfied Customer, Profitable Business

    For a bank or any other business that sells products or services, having a good number of satisfied customers makes all the difference. The customer keeps the business! Your satisfaction with the products and/or services is what keeps the company competitive and alive in the market. Without a certain number of satisfied customers, it is impossible to keep up. Customers are the source of profit for any business. Having customer feedback is important for the company to reduce the negative impacts of its activities. In the same way, seek to improve the solution offered in an effective, innovative and creative way. Listening to the customer is very important for market expansion and brand credibility. Thus, the organization will show that it is always concerned with generating value for those who consume it.

    Para um banco ou qualquer outro negócio que venda produtos ou serviços, ter um número bom clientes satisfeitos faz toda a diferença. O cliente é que mantém o negócio! Sua satisfação com os produtos e/ou serviços é que mantem a empresa competitiva e viva no mercado. Sem um certo número de clientes satisfeito, é impossível manter-se. São os clientes a fonte de lucro de qualquer negócio. Ter um feedback do cliente é importante para que a empresa reduza os impactos negativos das suas atividades. Da mesma forma, busque aprimorar a solução oferecida de forma eficaz, inovadora e criativa. Ouvir o cliente é muito importante para a expansão do mercado e credibilidade da marca. Assim, a organização mostrará que está sempre preocupado em gerar valor para quem o consome.

    2.2 Net Promoter Score (NPS)

    The NPS is a methodology that was created in the USA by the scholar Fred Reichheld. Its purpose is to measure the degree of satisfaction of any company's consumers. In his book,The Ultimate Question, he shows you that you owe the customer a question. Would you recommend our company to a friend or relative? From there, you can fit them into 3 large groups. They are: promoters, detractors and neutrals. Promoters. Customers who answer YES and are customers who love your products. They will be the promoters, able to recommend your company to their friends. Detractors. It's the customers who answer No. These are the people you need to be on the lookout for and act fast. Understand the reason for this negative feedback and act urgently! There are also Neutrals, but let's focus on DETRACTORS!

    The NPS é uma metodologia que foi criada nos EUA pelo estudioso Fred Reichheld. Seu intuito é de mensurar o grau de satisfação dos consumidores de qualquer empresa. Em seu livro, A Pergunta Definitiva ele mostra que você deve uma pergunta para o cliente. Você recomendaria a nossa empresa para um amigo ou parente? A partir daí, você consegue encaixá-los em 3 grandes grupos. São eles: promotores, detratores e neutros. Promotores. Os clientes que respondem SIM e são clientes que amam seus produtos. Eles serão os promotores, capazes de recomendar sua empresa para seus amigos. Detratores. São os clientes que respondem Não.Estas são as pessoas que você precisa ficar atento e agir rápido. Entenda o motivo desse feedback negativo e ajir com urgência! Existem também os Neutros, mas vamos manter o foco nos DETRATORES!

    Business Goal - Increase NPS

    To find out your company's NPS, get the total percentage for each group, in this case, DETRACTORS AND PROMOTERS. This is done by dividing the group total by the total number of registered ratings. Subtract the total percentage of “Detractors” from the total percentage of “Promoters”. So you will have your NPS. NPS = % Promoters - % Detractors Ideally, your score is always above or equal to 9. This will mean that your customers are promoters of your brand. NPS value can be classified in 3 ways. 0 to 6. Improvement zone, with a large volume of detractors and neutrals. 6 to 8. Quality zone. In other words, the company has more neutral customers and promoters than detractors. 8 to 10. Zone of perfection. In other words, the company has a high rate of promoting clients and few detractors.

    Para descobrir o NPS da sua empresa, obtenha o percentual total de cada grupo, neste caso, DETRATORES E PROMOTORES. Isso se faz dividindo o total do grupo pelo total de avaliações resgistradas. Subtraia o percentual total de “Detratores” do percentual total de “Promotores”. Assim, você terá seu NPS. NPS = % Promotores – % Detratores O ideal é que seu resultado esteja sempre acima ou igual a 9. Isso irá significa que os seus clientes são promotores da sua marca. Os valores do NPS podem ser classificados de 3 formas. 0 a 6. Zona de aperfeiçoamento, com grande volume de detratores e neutros. 6 a 8. Zona de qualidade. Em outras palavras, a empresa possui mais clientes neutros e promotores do que detratores. 8 a 10. Zona de perfeição. Ou seja, a empresa possui alto índice de clientes promotores e poucos detratores.

    Business Strategy

    Using the database provided, generate a predictive model that generates a forecast of the probability of a customer to assess themselves as dissatisfied with the bank and with this information initiate Marketing actions and/or offers of new products and services to change this probability, increasing thus the NPS index. By market statistics, 1 dissatisfied customer generates 3 more, and so on. Taking this statistic to the opposite, in addition to keeping the current customer, we still have the possibility of raising more 3 customers for the organization with actions focused only on the current customer, which is much easier, profitable and with less investment.

    Usando a base de dados fornecida, gerar um modelo preditivo que gere uma previsão de probalilidade de um cliente avaliar como insatisfeito com o banco e com esta informação inicar ações de Marketing e/ou ofertas de novos produtos e serviços para mudar esta probalidade, aumentando assim o índice NPS. Pelas estatísticas de mercado, 1 cliente insatisfeito geram mais 3 e assim por diante. Levando esta estatítica para o inverso, além de mantermos o cliente atual, ainda temos a possibilidade de argariar mais 3 clientes para a organização com ações focadas apenas no cliente atual que é muito mais fácil, rentável e com menos investimento.

7.0 Target Variable Balancing

In [37]:
# Let´s check now the balance of target values in Dataset
In [38]:
# Check Target Column Balance
df_cln.groupBy('TARGET').count().show()

+------+-----+
|TARGET|count|
+------+-----+
|     1| 3008|
|     0|73012|
+------+-----+

As observed 👆👆, it seems be unbalanced. With this way, the model will learn more about Good Evaluation (TARGET = 0) than Bad Evaluation (TARGET = 1).

Our goal is to have a model with Balancing Learning.

There is a need to apply a oversample strategy in order to ballance target values in dataset

In [40]:
# Getting rows witn Target = 0
major_class_0 = df_cln.filter(f.col("TARGET") == 0)
In [41]:
# Getting rows witn Target = 0
minor_class_1 = df_cln.filter(f.col("TARGET") == 1)
In [42]:
# Showing rows number witn Target = 1 (Bad Evaluation)
minor_class_1.count()
Out[42]:
3008
In [43]:
# Showing rows number witn Target = 0 (Good Evaluation)
major_class_0.count()
Out[43]:
73012
In [44]:
# major_class_0.count() /  minor_class_1.count() = 24X more with Target = 0
a = range(24)
oversampled_df = minor_class_1.withColumn("dummy", f.explode(f.array([f.lit(x) for x in a]))).drop('dummy')
In [45]:
# 72192 Samples with Target = 0 created
oversampled_df.count()
Out[45]:
72192
In [46]:
# combine both oversampled minority rows and previous majority rows 
combined_df = major_class_0.unionAll(oversampled_df)
combined_df.count()
Out[46]:
145204
In [47]:
combined_df.groupBy('TARGET').count().show()

+------+-----+
|TARGET|count|
+------+-----+
|     1|72192|
|     0|73012|
+------+-----+

As observed 👆👆, NOW it seems be balanced. With this way, the model will learn balanced about Good Evaluation (TARGET = 0) and Bad Evaluation (TARGET = 1).

10.0 Hyper Parameters Tuning

In [73]:
# Tuning RandomForest Hyper Parameters
In [74]:
# Preparing a Vector Assembler Object needed in Tuning Process
feature_list = []
for col in bankDF_blcd_scld.columns:
    if col == 'label':
        continue
    else:
        feature_list.append(col)
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_list, outputCol="features")
In [75]:
# Creating Random Forest Object for Tuning
rfClassifier_tng = RandomForestClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features")
In [76]:
# Creating Pipeline Oject for Tuning
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[assembler, rfClassifier_tng])
In [77]:
# Creating Grid Oject for Tuning using:
# Random Forest Object
# NumTrees Parameter with range within 10 and 50
# MaxDepth Parameter with rande within 5 and 25

paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder() \
   .addGrid(rfClassifier_tng.numTrees, [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 10, stop = 50, num = 3)]) \
   .addGrid(rfClassifier_tng.maxDepth, [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 5, stop = 25, num = 3)]) \
   .build()
In [78]:
# Creating a CrossValidator and BinaryClassificationEvaluator objects for Tuning
crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline,
                          estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,
                          evaluator=BinaryClassificationEvaluator(),
                          numFolds=3)
In [79]:
# Splitting Training Data in one for Training and other for Test, now based on Balanced and SCALED Dataset for Tuning
(train_data_tng, test_data_tng) = bankDF_blcd_scld.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2])
In [80]:
# Processing Hyper Parameters Tuning
Model_tnded = crossval.fit(train_data_tng)
In [81]:
# Getting Predictions with Model Tuned passing Test Data 
predictions_tnded = Model_tnded.transform(test_data_tng)
In [82]:
# Evaluating Model Tuned
evaluator_tnded = BinaryClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="label", rawPredictionCol="prediction")
In [83]:
# Getting Evaluation of Model Tuned
result_tnded = evaluator_tnded.evaluate(predictions_tnded)
In [84]:
# Print Evaluation
result_tnded

11.0 Final Considerations

11.1 Business Initiatives with Final Predict Model

Nowadays, the Santander Bank NPS is 96% that is a excellent index.
But there is a model to do it better.
With this predict model, there is business opportunity below:
* Each mounth, Marketing and/or Retention Departments receive a report with the id, customer name and predict target igual 1 that is a bad evaluation.
* Based on this report, theses departments can contact theses customers and make assement with him BEFORE HIS BAD EVALUTION.

11.1 Iniciativas de negócios com modelo de previsão final

Hoje, o NPS do Banco Santander está em 96%, um excelente índice.
Mas existe um modelo para fazer melhor.
Com este modelo de previsão, há oportunidade de negócios abaixo:
* A cada mês, os Departamentos de Marketing e / ou Retenção recebem um relatório com o id, nome do cliente e previsão de target igual 1 que é uma avaliação ruim.
* Com base neste relatório, esses departamentos podem contatar esses clientes e fazer avaliações com ele ANTES DE SUA MÁ AVALIAÇÃO.

11.2 Final Predict Model Monetary Returns

With 85% of accuracy, it means that a each 10 customers evaluated by the model that have trend to evalute the bank as BAD, it is right in 85% of cases!
Supose that with 1000 clients evaluated by model that probabily will evaluate the Bank as BAD, the departments make a proacitve actions and revert 850 clients, the monetary return will 850 * US 10,00 per mounth, per client reverted, that is US 102,000.00/year of profit.

11.2 Retornos monetários do modelo de previsão final

Com 85% de acerto, significa que a cada 10 clientes avaliados pelo modelo que têm tendência a avaliar o banco como RUIM, acertou em 85% dos casos!
Suponha que com 1000 clientes avaliados pelo modelo que provavelmente avaliarão o Banco como BAD, os departamentos realizam ações pró-ativas e revertem 850 clientes, o retorno monetário será de 850 * US 10,00 por mês, por cliente revertido, ou seja US 102.000,00 / ano de lucro.
